<article>
    <h1>SPICY RICE AND NOO&#xAD;DLE BOWLS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201002/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-02"><time>2020-10-02</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHO&#xAD;TOS: CHENGDU BOWL, CRYS&#xAD;TAL JADE GROUP, GOOD&#xAD;WOOD PARK HO&#xAD;TEL, LE VYR</span>
    </section>

    <p>If you find reg­u­lar grain bowls too bland and bor­ing, head to Chengdu Bowl – a spin-off con­cept by Chengdu Restau­rant in Amoy Street – for a good dose of spice.</p>
    <p>Take­away is also avail­able from Chengdu Restau­rant’s sis­ter out­let Taikoo Lane at Chi­na­town Point.</p>
    <p>No bland chicken breast on salad here. Think la zi ji (Sichuan mala chicken), spicy sliced beef or juicy pork belly (above) over pearl rice or whole­grain brown rice (from $10.60 for a small por­tion).</p>
    <p>Sides in­clude corn, edamame, xiao bai cai and pre­served veg­eta­bles. Toss the in­gre­di­ents to­gether to get a bit of every­thing in one bite.</p>
    <p>Aside from the stan­dard rice bowls, my two top picks are the Prawn Paste Noo­dles with Sour Pick­led Soup (from $10.60) and Sichuan Spicy Mao­cai ($13.80).</p>
    <p>Both pack a tongue-tin­gling punch.</p>
    <p>The house­made prawn paste balls have a nice chew and I slurp the springy noo­dles with the sour and spicy soup.</p>
    <p>The mao­cai, a Sichuan stew, has all my favourite in­gre­di­ents that pair well with mala – sliced lo­tus root, soya bean sprouts, lun­cheon meat, fun­gus and enoki. It comes with rice, which you will need to bal­ance out the heat.</p>
    <p>OPEN: 10am to 8.30pm daily</p>
    <p>INFO: Or­der on­line at cheng­dubowl.ezqr.sg,</p>
    <p>GrabFood and De­liv­eroo</p>

